WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.720
Quarto Dashboards is a new feature that is coming to Quarto in the 1.4 release, and it's

00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:16.799
something that we really decided to add on the heels of the most recent Posit conference,

00:00:16.799 --> 00:00:20.040
and so it wasn't originally on the plan for 1.4, but we decided to take a little bit of

00:00:20.040 --> 00:00:23.440
extra time and see if we could squeeze it in.

00:00:23.440 --> 00:00:29.440
Obviously the goal of Quarto Dashboards is pretty simple, make it easy to build compelling

00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:37.599
interactive dashboards using R, Python, Julia, Observable, and very much sort of heritage

00:00:37.599 --> 00:00:42.320
of Flex Dashboard, so very much sort of bring Flex Dashboard and that type of experience

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:47.680
into Quarto, incorporate everything we've learned, everything the company has built,

00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:53.279
and try to bring that together into a really great experience for our users.

00:00:53.279 --> 00:00:56.599
Dashboards in Quarto are pretty straightforward.

00:00:56.599 --> 00:01:00.279
They're basically composed of cards, so you can think about cards as just sort of the

00:01:00.279 --> 00:01:05.239
units, the atomic units that you're arranging in a dashboard, and you arrange those cards

00:01:05.239 --> 00:01:11.279
into rows and columns to lay them out, and then you can use things like pages, tab sets,

00:01:11.279 --> 00:01:16.000
and sidebars to sort of incorporate more advanced layout, to incorporate controls and other

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.959
things that might need to appear in the dashboard.

00:01:19.959 --> 00:01:25.760
But with those simple building blocks, it's actually pretty easy to build some cool dashboards.

00:01:25.760 --> 00:01:28.040
So let's build a simple dashboard.

00:01:28.040 --> 00:01:29.239
Let's see if we can do this.

00:01:29.239 --> 00:01:32.639
So let's just start from scratch.

00:01:32.639 --> 00:01:38.040
I've got a QMD that I've got going here, and I'm just going to start with the front matter,

00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:45.239
my dashboard, and let's make it format dashboard.

00:01:45.239 --> 00:01:51.639
And then let's just put in, for now, we're going to explore my lack of R programming

00:01:51.639 --> 00:01:58.320
skills, but let's just put in a simple static plot to start, and then let's have a look

00:01:58.320 --> 00:02:00.260
at what we get.

00:02:00.260 --> 00:02:08.639
And so, whoops, we're not quite fitting on the screen, hang on, there we go.

00:02:08.639 --> 00:02:12.440
And so you can see now I've gotten, okay, I guess I've gotten, you know, a little title

00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:17.800
bar, I've gotten one big card, and so you can see, you know, the treatment is already

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:22.279
a little different than just a simple web page, because we're sort of filling the whole

00:02:22.279 --> 00:02:23.279
screen.

00:02:23.279 --> 00:02:30.800
And in fact, as we add elements to this dashboard, like let's add a second plot to this dashboard,

00:02:30.800 --> 00:02:33.220
it sort of knows enough to lay things out appropriately.

00:02:33.220 --> 00:02:39.000
So it just made two different cards here, and the cards contain the visualization.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:43.559
But of course, I may want to start to do some cooler things to sort of tune this up a little

00:02:43.559 --> 00:02:44.559
bit.

00:02:45.240 --> 00:02:48.559
Let's start by putting a title on some of these cards.

00:02:48.559 --> 00:02:56.360
So let's go title, you know, cars plot, and then we'll add a title down here, MT cars

00:02:56.360 --> 00:03:00.860
plot.

00:03:00.860 --> 00:03:04.479
You know, and we're starting to starting to see, okay, now we're getting it's getting

00:03:04.479 --> 00:03:05.479
better.

00:03:05.479 --> 00:03:09.919
I wonder if those might look better side by side.

00:03:09.919 --> 00:03:14.240
Well, in Cordo dashboards, you use headings to arrange things.

00:03:14.919 --> 00:03:21.479
And so by adding a simple heading, I can basically say, okay, I'd like to, you know, I guess

00:03:21.479 --> 00:03:25.919
maybe maybe the way to explain it is to do this is to say, you know, dashboards have

00:03:25.919 --> 00:03:30.199
sort of an orientation, which by default is rows.

00:03:30.199 --> 00:03:35.479
So by default, it's saying just everything that shows up is a row, I could change that

00:03:35.479 --> 00:03:39.399
and say, actually, like, let's make everything columns instead.

00:03:39.399 --> 00:03:44.559
And so when I do that, we'll actually get the layout now into columns.

00:03:44.559 --> 00:03:50.279
Similarly, if I said, let's go back to rows, just a good old basic orientation that we

00:03:50.279 --> 00:03:51.279
had.

00:03:51.279 --> 00:03:56.300
If I said I want to make a row explicitly, I can add a heading and say, here's a row

00:03:56.300 --> 00:03:57.300
that I made.

00:03:57.300 --> 00:04:03.800
And so I made a row, and the row has two things side by side in it, it'll get even easier

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:08.199
to see if I do something like make another row and put some content in it.

00:04:08.199 --> 00:04:14.839
Here's some content.

00:04:14.839 --> 00:04:24.359
So now I have made a dashboard that basically has here, a row with some content in it, and

00:04:24.359 --> 00:04:27.239
then here a row with the plots in it.

00:04:27.239 --> 00:04:31.179
And you can see that looks very straightforward.

00:04:31.179 --> 00:04:37.059
And so that gives you the basic idea of arranging things now, you know, you can keep going.

00:04:37.059 --> 00:04:43.059
So you know, I could say, I'm going to make a column inside here.

00:04:43.059 --> 00:04:45.940
And then I'm going to make another column.

00:04:45.940 --> 00:04:51.380
And I will put another plot inside that column.

00:04:51.380 --> 00:04:57.760
So I'll put another plot cars in here.

00:04:57.760 --> 00:05:02.380
And so you can see you can you can make some pretty fancy layouts with some pretty simple

00:05:02.380 --> 00:05:08.380
constructs with just using headings to arrange content.

00:05:08.380 --> 00:05:15.260
But you know, maybe maybe it's, you want to do something cooler, you know, so for example,

00:05:15.260 --> 00:05:21.059
maybe instead of instead of putting these side by side like that, we want to make them

00:05:21.059 --> 00:05:24.000
in tabs.

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:29.059
So we can just add a tab set to our column heading right there.

00:05:29.059 --> 00:05:31.459
And now we've got them in tabs.

00:05:31.579 --> 00:05:34.220
So that's pretty cool.

00:05:34.220 --> 00:05:40.100
You know, but maybe we don't even want them in tabs, maybe we want them on separate pages.

00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:51.619
So why don't we put a heading one right here, and we'll make a page and a page, page two.

00:05:51.619 --> 00:05:54.459
And now we've arranged them on completely standalone pages.

00:05:54.459 --> 00:05:59.019
And in fact, we could have very fancy layouts on each of these two pages.

00:05:59.019 --> 00:06:04.739
And so you can see the, you know, some some important concepts at work here.

00:06:04.739 --> 00:06:08.660
So one important concept is these code cells are very, very primary.

00:06:08.660 --> 00:06:11.380
So these code cells are automatically making cards.

00:06:11.380 --> 00:06:14.100
And so that means you don't really have to do a lot of work.

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:18.380
You know, you basically can make code cells that create visualizations, and then place

00:06:18.380 --> 00:06:24.980
some simple markdown around the outside to provide the layout and orientation.

00:06:24.980 --> 00:06:29.660
The second is you can see, you know, the the headings and the markdown that you need

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:37.720
to add to create these layouts is really straightforward, and hopefully very, very intuitive.

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:40.100
So that's gives you some of the basic ideas.

00:06:40.100 --> 00:06:42.700
Now there's, of course, there's more you can do.

00:06:42.700 --> 00:06:46.480
You know, you can do things like add additional navigation.

00:06:46.480 --> 00:06:51.380
So I could say like, I want a Twitter sharing link.

00:06:51.380 --> 00:06:55.059
And then I want a GitHub link to the repo.

00:06:55.059 --> 00:07:00.380
And then, you know, we'll automatically do the right thing and figure out your GitHub

00:07:00.380 --> 00:07:02.380
URL and put a sharing URL.

00:07:02.380 --> 00:07:06.579
So you can very quickly get some pretty nice things.

00:07:06.579 --> 00:07:10.140
There are more things you can do than just cards.

00:07:10.140 --> 00:07:19.500
So for example, you know, you could do a row that's got what are called value boxes.

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:24.140
Value boxes, you probably are familiar with from bslib.

00:07:24.140 --> 00:07:29.540
But if I want to make a value box here, I can make a code cell.

00:07:29.540 --> 00:07:35.339
And then I can just say, this code cell is a value box.

00:07:35.339 --> 00:07:40.480
And then this code cell really just needs to return a list that describes what we want

00:07:40.480 --> 00:07:41.480
to show here.

00:07:41.480 --> 00:07:50.600
So let's just say my value is 26.

00:07:50.600 --> 00:07:54.040
The color is going to be red.

00:07:54.040 --> 00:08:00.720
And let's even put an icon on it for like envelope.

00:08:00.720 --> 00:08:06.040
And then let's make two of those just because it'll look a little cooler.

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:12.239
Now we've got a red and a green value box that we've created.

00:08:12.239 --> 00:08:13.239
And there they are.

00:08:13.239 --> 00:08:15.040
They've showed up just as you'd expect.

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:19.559
And what's great about this is now these value boxes, of course, since they're built programmatically,

00:08:19.559 --> 00:08:20.559
can be responsive.

00:08:20.559 --> 00:08:24.079
You know, so obviously, they can be red and green.

00:08:24.079 --> 00:08:28.119
The icons can update to reflect the status.

00:08:28.119 --> 00:08:34.080
And so it's super straightforward now to make these types of arrangements using this Cordo

00:08:34.080 --> 00:08:35.080
dashboard.

00:08:35.679 --> 00:08:40.900
Now, I think the other thing to think about and one other area that we focused on was

00:08:40.900 --> 00:08:46.919
trying to create experiences that were great inside notebooks as well.

00:08:46.919 --> 00:08:49.080
And so here I've got a Jupyter notebook.

00:08:49.080 --> 00:08:51.359
I was showing you a Cordo markdown document.

00:08:51.359 --> 00:08:55.679
Now I've got a Jupyter notebook that's building a dashboard as well.

00:08:55.679 --> 00:09:02.599
And part of what's great about using the cells as sort of atomic units, as you can see, this

00:09:02.599 --> 00:09:09.520
notebook, which basically makes a pretty nice dashboard, is, you know, has some markdown

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:14.520
cells, but really is just a set of code cells with a little bit of markdown around it to

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:16.159
arrange it.

00:09:16.159 --> 00:09:29.760
And if we actually open up a terminal here and actually preview this, Cordo preview Gapminder.

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:40.200
So if we actually preview this Jupyter notebook, we will see here's the dashboard that that

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:41.200
creates.

00:09:41.200 --> 00:09:47.559
And so, you know, you can go and create pretty great authoring experiences inside notebooks

00:09:47.559 --> 00:09:55.799
even for building these really nice and robust Cordo dashboards.

00:09:55.799 --> 00:10:05.239
And so I think the last little bit for me to talk about is just give you a quick look,

00:10:05.239 --> 00:10:09.400
a preview of some interactivity.

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:17.200
So let me just get back to so a couple examples of interactive dashboards.

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:21.479
And so, you know, obviously the static dashboards that I showed you help you understand the

00:10:21.479 --> 00:10:23.119
layout.

00:10:23.119 --> 00:10:30.000
But here's a nice dashboard that shows some of the interactivity and how straightforward

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.359
it is to incorporate things like Shiny into these dashboards.

00:10:33.359 --> 00:10:35.919
So you know, this is all pretty cool.

00:10:35.919 --> 00:10:40.679
But what's really cool is when you look at the actual source behind it, and you see how

00:10:40.679 --> 00:10:47.280
straightforward the source is, we've made a sidebar, we have the main plot, we have

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:52.640
the data, the data page, and then we've just mixed some code cells in there that create

00:10:52.640 --> 00:10:56.760
the various inputs that actually render the plot.

00:10:56.760 --> 00:10:59.359
And all of that works just beautifully.

00:10:59.359 --> 00:11:04.960
And so it's really straightforward to make both fancy layouts and also pretty impressive

00:11:04.960 --> 00:11:08.119
interactive dashboards.

00:11:08.119 --> 00:11:11.200
As I said, this is coming in Cordo 1.4.

00:11:11.200 --> 00:11:14.880
I think we anticipate that early next year.

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:21.400
And I wanted to highlight, I think, one other thing, which is over the past two weeks, we've

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:23.520
been working hard on this feature.

00:11:23.520 --> 00:11:28.919
But the rest of the company has chipped in in a great way by helping us both test and

00:11:28.919 --> 00:11:32.440
generate a huge number of sample dashboards.

00:11:32.440 --> 00:11:36.159
We appreciate everyone's effort and support doing that.

00:11:36.159 --> 00:11:40.320
I have found a number of really great bugs as a result of all that testing, a few of

00:11:40.320 --> 00:11:43.039
which are still open, but I'm getting through them.

00:11:43.039 --> 00:11:48.419
And we also have probably 20 great samples on the Cordo website, most of which were contributed

00:11:48.419 --> 00:11:50.000
by other members of the company.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:56.320
So thanks to all for your support as we sort of grind really hard to try to get this into

00:11:56.320 --> 00:11:58.359
Cordo 1.4 unexpectedly.

00:11:58.359 --> 00:11:59.359
So thanks all.

00:11:59.359 --> 00:12:01.320
And hopefully people like what they see.

